solution:
We have that
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} (5)(-1) - (5)(-1) \\ (4)(-1) - (4)(-1) \\ (4)(5) - (4)(5) \end{pmatrix} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}.\]More generally, the cross product of any vector with itself is the zero vector.
model_solution:
Step 1: The cross product of two vectors is given by the formula $\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \\ a_3 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} b_1 \\ b_2 \\ b_3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} a_2 b_3 - a_3 b_2 \\ a_3 b_1 - a_1 b_3 \\ a_1 b_2 - a_2 b_1 \end{pmatrix}.$ 

$\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 (-1) - (-1) 5 \\ (-1) 4 - 4 (-1) \\ 4 5 - 5 4 \end{pmatrix}$
Step 2: Evaluate the expression to get $\begin{pmatrix} -5 + 5 \\ -4 + 4 \\ 20 - 20 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$
Step 3: The result of the cross product of a vector with itself is the zero vector.
Step 4: The final answer is $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}$.
